{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637530"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:43:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:43:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17666"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17666"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.61,0.14,0.03,0.14,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10380"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78466"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10380"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63828"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10543"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24268"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25006"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78466"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMechanisms of carbon dioxide transport help in understanding acid-base balance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the predominant form of carbon dioxide transport in blood?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["As bicarbonate in plasma and red blood cells","As carbonic acid","Dissolved in plasma","Bound to haemoglobin","As carbaminohaemoglobin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe majority of carbon dioxide transport occurs as \u003Cstrong\u003Ebicarbonate in plasma and red blood cells\u003C/strong\u003E. This form accounts for roughly 70% of total CO2 transport and relies on the enzyme carbonic anhydrase found within erythrocytes to facilitate the conversion process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlternative transport mechanisms are less significant:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAs carbonic acid\u003C/strong\u003E represents a brief intermediate state that quickly breaks down to form bicarbonate and hydrogen ions, making it unsuitable for transport\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDissolved in plasma\u003C/strong\u003E represents just 5% of CO2 transport capacity. While this form enables pulmonary gas exchange, it cannot meet systemic transport requirements\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBound to haemoglobin\u003C/strong\u003E accounts for approximately 20% of CO2 transport through formation of carbamino compounds at amino terminals\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAs carbaminohaemoglobin\u003C/strong\u003E specifically refers to CO2 bound to haemoglobin proteins, contributing roughly 5% to total transport. This mechanism becomes more relevant in deoxygenated blood\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo maintain electrical balance, bicarbonate ions leave red blood cells in exchange for chloride ions through a process known as the chloride shift or Hamburger phenomenon.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Most carbon dioxide in blood (70%) exists as bicarbonate ions, while smaller fractions are dissolved (5%) or bound to proteins (25%).","Red blood cells contain carbonic anhydrase which facilitates the conversion between carbon dioxide and bicarbonate.","Bicarbonate exits red blood cells through an exchange with chloride ions, preserving electrical neutrality across the membrane."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63828"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17666"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63828"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T21:04:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T00:02:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10380"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78466"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","n